                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d611">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/1681: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-07T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 7, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>35. At a conference of representatives of interested agencies held on January 6,
                    Treasury representative strongly urged that conclusion of reciprocal aid
                    agreement should be delayed pending Chinese reaction to the President’s reply
                    concerning the proposed loan. Representatives of War Department concurred.
                    (Department’s no. 7, January 1, 9 p.m.)</p>
                <p>It is therefore not believed advisable that you take any action for the time
                    being in regard to the reciprocal aid agreement. If this matter is mentioned by
                    the Chinese it is suggested you state simply that you have received no
                    instructions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
